# Voxel Project Architecture

## Project Structure

Use a **feature-based structure** with two main roots:

```
Assets/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Core/           # Shared domain logic, infrastructure, cross-cutting concerns
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Grid/       # Voxel grid, coordinates, spatial data
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Terrain/    # Terrain pipeline, height buffers, noise
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Pathfinding/
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Data/       # Shared data types, registries, definitions
‚îÇ
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Features/       # Feature modules, co-located by capability
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ UI/         # HUD, panels, UI controllers + .uxml/.uss
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Actors/     # Actor behaviors, spawning, pathing
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Placement/  # Object placement, preview, validation
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ ...
```

**Co-locate** related files: scripts, UXML, USS, and feature-specific data in the same feature folder.

## Separate Business Logic from Unity Code

- **Domain layer**: Pure C# classes with no `UnityEngine` dependencies. Game rules, calculations, state machines.
- **Unity layer**: MonoBehaviours, ScriptableObjects, and components that **wire** domain logic to Unity APIs.
- **Rule**: Domain types live in `Core/` or feature folders; they must not reference `MonoBehaviour`, `GameObject`, `Transform`, or `UnityEngine.Object`.

```csharp
// ‚ùå BAD: Business logic mixed with Unity
public class BuildingInventory : MonoBehaviour
{
    void Update()
    {
        var count = GetComponent<ItemRegistry>().GetDefinition(item).MaxStack; // Unity in hot path
    }
}

// ‚úÖ GOOD: Domain logic separate, Unity only wires it
// Core/Inventory/InventoryService.cs - no UnityEngine
public class InventoryService
{
    public int GetMaxStack(Item item, IItemRegistry registry) => registry.GetDefinition(item)?.MaxStack ?? 0;
}
// Features/Inventory/InventoryController.cs - MonoBehaviour wires UI to InventoryService
```

## Production-Grade Patterns

- **Dependency injection**: Prefer constructor injection for domain services; use `[SerializeField]` or service locator only for Unity-bound wiring.
- **Interfaces for Unity types**: Define `IItemRegistry`, `IPlacedObjectRegistry` etc. so domain code depends on abstractions, not ScriptableObjects.
- **Single responsibility**: Controllers handle input/Unity lifecycle; services handle business logic; data types are immutable where possible.

## Documentation & References

- **Use current documentation**: When referencing Unity, C#, or third-party APIs, fetch and cite up-to-date docs (e.g. Unity 6.3 Manual).
- **Verify freshness**: Run `date` in CLI to establish current context before assuming doc or version info is current.
- Prefer official sources; avoid outdated blog posts or deprecated API patterns.

## Planning & Refactoring

When planning modifications to existing code:

- **Assess first**: Check for bloat (unused code, oversized classes, duplicated logic) and mixed concerns (Unity + domain in one class, multiple responsibilities).
- **Consider structured refactor**: If issues exist, plan a refactor before adding features‚Äîextract domain logic, split responsibilities, consolidate duplicates.
- **Incremental over big-bang**: Prefer small, testable refactor steps; avoid rewriting large files in one pass.
